            <fr:ul><fr:li>a type is <fr:em><fr:strong><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[-2]]></fr:tex>-truncated</html:span></fr:strong></fr:em> when it is <fr:link href="foreign-erct-erct-001H.xml" title="Contractible type" addr="//erct/erct-001H" type="local">contractible</fr:link>;</fr:li>
  <fr:li>a type is <fr:em><fr:strong><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[-1]]></fr:tex>-truncated</html:span></fr:strong></fr:em> when it is a <fr:link href="foreign-erct-erct-001I.xml" title="Proposition" addr="//erct/erct-001I" type="local">proposition</fr:link>;</fr:li>
  <fr:li>for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n \geq  0]]></fr:tex>, a type <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em><fr:strong><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-truncated</html:span></fr:strong></fr:em> when for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x,y:A]]></fr:tex> the identification type <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x=y]]></fr:tex> is <html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n-1]]></fr:tex>-truncated</html:span>.</fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>So, in particular, a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0]]></fr:tex>-truncated type is precisely a <fr:em>set</fr:em>. We shall often refer to <html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-truncated</html:span> types as <fr:em><fr:strong><html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-types</html:span></fr:strong></fr:em>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
